{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5b6bbec2-a5a0-4698-8efc-7bfbfae05c58","content":"In .NET MAUI, lifecycle handling moved from `Application` to the `Window` class. Override `CreateWindow` and use a custom `Window` subclass:\n\n```csharp\npublic class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n        => new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n}\n\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()      // ← OnStart\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnDeactivated()  // ← OnSleep\n    {\n        base.OnDeactivated();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()      // ← OnResume\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key mappings:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnDeactivated()` / `OnBackgrounding()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` / `OnActivated()` |\n\n`OnBackgrounding()` is closer to `OnSleep` semantically (app going to background), while `OnDeactivated` fires when the window loses focus. Choose based on your use case.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"decca1ff-aa1d-45e5-84ff-f59b2728134f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. Specifically:\n\n- The `Application` class still exists, but lifecycle handling moved to the `Window` class.\n- You override `CreateWindow()` and can hook into window lifecycle events, or override methods on a custom `Window` subclass.\n\n\n- `OnStart` maps to `Window.Created` or `OnCreated()`, `OnSleep` maps to `Window.Deactivated` or `Backgrounding` events, and `OnResume` maps to `Window.Activated` or `Resumed` events.\n- Alternatively, you can configure platform-specific lifecycle events directly in `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`.","outputTokens":627,"requestId":"B7D0:2A1B2F:14A214:1AD835:69FFD859"},"id":"def91bd4-f07b-4894-ac7b-ebccaf68ff3a","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:59:17.189Z","parentId":"b9bc861e-0db3-4ead-936b-97df5ed13788"}
